  608: bound > 0, and median Δ ≥ 0 under the stress regime, plus a guard to pause if the
  609: λ = 0 control itself exceeded 0.05. The result was **NO-GO**: the advantage was
  610: positive in all 18 primary cells, but the pre-registered pooled **median Δ = 0.025**,
  611: below the 0.05 rebuild gate; the λ = 0 negative control sat at ≈ 0.016, within the
  612: pause guard (no hidden asymmetry flagged). A **post-hoc** world-cluster
  613: ratio-of-sums estimate was Δ = 0.026 [0.023, 0.029] (Monte-Carlo uncertainty on the
  614: simulated data-generating process, reported separately from the median). The
  615: advantage rises with credit pressure λ and falls as credit aligns with value — the
  616: credit-versus-coverage mechanism — but it is small, which is why the calibrated
  617: multiplier is retired and the paper rests on the architecture and the mechanism
  618: direction, now sharpened by the robustness map below.
  619: 
  620: **A realistic-myopia extension (v1.14): a four-scenario robustness map.** The
  621: pre-registered gate above equips the central arm with competent, *harm-aware*
  622: appraisal. A v1.14 extension asks what happens when the central is realistically
  623: **myopic to harm on the low-visibility long tail** — where routine oversight,
  624: opposition and audit attention reach mainly the visible, contested few. It splits
  625: true value into support and harm, S = S⁺ − H, and gives the central a
  626: salience-gated harm term, M_C = a + b·S⁺ + w·(v_p − S⁺) − b_H·s(V)·H + η, whose
  627: harm-detection s(V) rises with a project's visibility; the distributed arm registers
  628: harm across the whole distribution. Holding the budget matched and scoring delivery
  629: on true value, four declared scenarios (plus one diagnostic contrast) level the field
  630: for both institutions, reported as the signed fraction of the full-information greedy
  631: benchmark, parity at zero (`npm run e4:scenarios`). At the **central's declared
  632: full-favourable endpoint** — low participation and a competent, harm-aware central —
  633: the *central wins*, delivering ≈ 98% of the benchmark against ≈ 68% for the
  634: distributed arm. Under the **probable** reference the distributed arm delivers ≈ 91%
  635: and the central ≈ 45%. At the **distributed-favourable** case the myopic central
  636: funds net-harmful projects and delivers *negative* value while the distributed arm
  637: delivers ≈ 96%. A diagnostic contrast that turns off harm-myopia *alone* (only the
  638: two harm-gate coordinates) accounts for about 40% of the sequential move from the
  639: probable gap; the further move to a fully harm-aware, competent **no-myopia bundle**
  640: returns the arms to near-parity — the same regime as the pre-registered gate's
  641: Δ ≈ 0.025, which by construction equipped the central with harm-aware appraisal. The
  642: two results are therefore the same phenomenon under opposite assumptions, not a
  643: contradiction: assume the central sees harm and the advantage collapses to the gate's
  644: near-parity; let it be realistically myopic and the coverage arm pulls ahead. A
  645: stylized joint-normal fixed-threshold benchmark (`research/e4-parity-theorem.md`)
  646: places the parity boundary at the equality of the two selectors' signal-to-noise
  647: covariance ratios, and a ceteris-paribus path from the probable to the
  648: central-favourable scenario crosses parity partway along the declared segment. These
  649: magnitudes are **source-motivated declared reference and stress points, not
  650: target-domain calibrated bands** (the intervals cover inner Monte-Carlo variability
  651: only, and the harm-myopia strength is the load-bearing, least-empirically-pinned
  652: assumption); the honest object is where each institution wins and how much the answer
  653: depends on that assumption, not a single number. Administrative-cost savings and
  654: corruption/leakage are separate, additive channels, deliberately excluded here.
  655: 
  656: **Finding 1: funding caps are an anti-concentration device, not a quality
  657: device.** With closure ON, concentration falls (funding Gini 0.732 vs
  658: 0.759), the most salient 5% of projects absorb less (16.8% vs 19.6% of all
  659: funding), and 15% more projects complete (25.3% vs 21.9%). But quality
  660: selection is unchanged (*sel(θ)*, the Pearson correlation across projects between
  661: latent quality θ and the binary indicator that a project reaches its funding
  662: target, ≈ 0.39 vs 0.41): the truncated surplus
  663: spills to the next most *visible* project, not the next *best* one. The
  664: architecture's claim for the closure rule should be — and in the corpus now
  665: is — bounded accordingly.
  666: 
  667: **Finding 2: the default anchor, not citizen attention, carries allocation
  668: quality.** A default-anchored mix, with a near-perfectly informed planner (r ≈
  669: 0.97), reaches sel(θ) ≈ 0.71: between 1.6× and 2× the salience-driven
  670: configurations (≈ 0.35–0.43). Quintupling citizen attention (α from 2% to
  671: 10%), by contrast, barely moves the needle —at most ≈ 0.08 in salience-driven
  672: regimes, and essentially nothing in default-anchored ones—, while degrading
  673: the vector's informational quality from near-perfect to moderate (r ≈ 0.97 →
  674: 0.55) costs ≈ 0.29 of selection. The anchor rules, not attention.
